The WWTP has developed and implemented a maintenance program (MP) to ensure the continued integrity of all of the equipment used to process, store or handle chlorine.  Chlorine is the only highly hazardous chemical used at the Facility.  The purpose of this MP is to reduce the risk of chlorine releases as a result of equipment failure and/or poor equipment maintenance. However, the Facility recognizes that a properly established program can have numerous other cost and production benefits beyond that of increasing safety. It is important to note that the Facility does have specific maintenance employees to perform mechanical integrity.  The Facility employees will be performing maintenance as needed and have developed an MP that will:
Minimize accidents, releases and water treatment delays caused by improper maintenance of equipment;
Minimize the number of pieces of equipment down for repair;
Stabilize the work load of the maintenance department; and
Reduce expenses by preventing excessive wear and breakdown, and by prolonging the life of the equipment.

In order to accomplish these goals, the MP has six major components designed to improve employee and process efficiency and safety, thereby reducing the risk of a chlorine release:
Equipment identification - Identification of all covered process equipment;
Periodic inspection and maintenance   Scheduling and performance is based on equipment age, past experience, and manufacturers' specifications and recommendations;
Employee training - Maintenance employee training is provided to ensure the continuation of a trained, knowledgeable workforce;
Corrective action - Requires inspection fol

low-up for noted equipment deficiencies;
New equipment installation - Installation of new equipment must undergo review and inspection; and
Inspection and test result records   Records are maintained in a central file in the Chief Operator?s Office for all work performed on covered process equipment.

  The WWTP provides written procedures that contain instructions that consider the following safety and health issues relevant to the use of chlorine in the water treatment process:
  Hazards and properties of chlorine
  Precautions necessary to prevent exposure, including engineering controls, administrative controls, and personal protective equipment
  Control measures to be taken if physical contact or airborne exposure occurs
  Quality control for raw materials and control for hazardous chemical inventory levels and any special or unique hazards of chlorine.

  The WWTP provides written operating procedures that contain clear instructions for safely conducting the following steps of each operating phase:
  1.  Initial startup;
  2.  Normal operations;
  3.  Temporary operations;
  4.  Emergency shutdown and conditions under which emergency shutdown is required; Assignment of shutdown responsibility to qualified operators to ensure that the shutdown is executed in a safe and timely manner; 
  5.  Emergency operations;
  6.  Normal shutdown; and
  7.  Startup following a turnaround, or after an emergency shutdown.

  The WWTP provides written operating procedures that contain clear instructions for safely working within operating limits including:
  1.  Consequences of deviation; and
  2.  Steps required to correct or avoid deviation.

